04404nam a22006615i 9781478012849DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780128497 a10.1515/97814780128492doi  a(DE-B1597)576384  a(OCoLC)1233040672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.H55bV364 2021 7aSOC0430002bisacsh04a305.895/9720732231 aVang, Ma, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistory on the Run :bSecrecy, Fugitivity, and Hmong Refugee Epistemologies /cMa Vang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (271 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Lost Bag and the Refugee Archive -- t1. Secrecy as Knowledge -- t2. Missing Things State Secrets and U.S. Cold War Policy toward Laos -- t3. The Refugee Soldier A Critique of Recognition and Citizenship in the Hmong Veterans’ Naturalization Act of 1997 -- t4. The Terrorist Ally The Case against General Vang Pao -- t5. The Refugee Grandmother Silence as Presence in The Latehomecomer and Gran Torino -- tEpilogue Geographic Stories for Refugee Return -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring its secret war in Laos (1961–1975), the United States recruited proxy soldiers among the Hmong people. Following the war, many of these Hmong soldiers migrated to the United States with refugee status. In History on the Run Ma Vang examines the experiences of Hmong refugees in the United States to theorize refugee histories and secrecy, in particular those of the Hmong. Vang conceptualizes these histories as fugitive histories, as they move and are carried by people who move. Charting the incomplete archives of the war made secret through redacted US state documents, ethnography, film, and literature, Vang shows how Hmong refugees tell their stories in ways that exist separately from narratives of U.S. empire and that cannot be traditionally archived. In so doing, Vang outlines a methodology for writing histories that foreground refugee epistemologies despite systematic attempts to silence those histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHmong (Asian people)zUnited States. 0aHmong AmericansxCultural assimilation. 0aHmong AmericansxHistory. 0aRefugeeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478012849?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012849/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZDB-23-DSLb2021